# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ducky-yount
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The **Baltimore Terrapins** were a team in the short-lived Federal League of professional baseball from 1914 to 1915.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Their brief existence led to litigation that led to an important legal precedent in baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The team played its home games at Terrapin Park.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Most of the professional baseball teams in Baltimore have been called the Orioles, in reference to the Baltimore oriole bird.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] There was already a minor league Baltimore Orioles, and the new Federal League club built their ballpark directly across the street from the Orioles park.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The new club chose to call itself the Baltimore Terrapins, after the diamondback terrapin, the state reptile of Maryland.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] That nickname would later become primarily associated with the University of Maryland, College Park sports teams called the Maryland Terrapins.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore gathered for spring training in Southern Pines, North Carolina at the Southern Pines Golf Club, previously used by the Philadelphia Phillies in 1909 and 1910.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Terrapins manager Otto Knabe had played for these Phillies teams and trained in Southern Pines.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] While the 1914 team posted a respectable 84–70 record and finished only 4½ games out of first place under player-manager Otto Knabe, the team was less than successful at the box office, even though four of the eight teams in the league (Chicago, Brooklyn, Pittsburgh, and St.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) were competing with one and even two (Chicago and St.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Louis) other major league teams in the same cities.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] In an attempt to turn this situation around and attract a marquee player to help them at the box office, the 1915 team recruited Chief Bender of the American League champion Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The Athletics had sold off several future Hall-of-Famers like Eddie Plank, Eddie Collins and Frank "Home Run" Baker after being swept by the surprising Boston Braves in the 1914 World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Bender had come off an impressive 17–3 season where he compiled seven shutouts and a 2.26 ERA in 1914.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] However, his 1915 season at Baltimore was a low point of his Hall of Fame career when he slumped to a 4–16 record, no shutouts, and a 3.99 ERA.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Baltimore's collapse to a 47–107 record, 40 games out of first, was overshadowed only by the collapse of Bender's former team who went from a 99–53 league championship season to a dismal 43–109 record, 58½ games out of first in 1915.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Bender and the Baltimore Terrapins never made a full recovery from 1915.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The incident did show the Federal League could compete seriously with the National League and American League on a professional baseball level and led to the buy-out truce which ended the Federal League for good.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] However, the Baltimore team's owners were not offered a part in this buyout.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] When the Federal League started, the Terrapins severely cut into the minor league Baltimore Orioles' attendance, causing financial problems for the owner.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] As a result, several players, including the young left-handed pitcher Babe Ruth, were offered for sale to major league teams.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Ruth's contract was purchased by the Boston Red Sox, after being turned down by Connie Mack and the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] In 1914, Ruth began his career with the Red Sox of the rival American League.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] After the demise of the Federal League and the Terrapins, Baltimore would not see major league baseball again until 1954, when the former St.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Louis Browns moved into town and became the present-day Baltimore Orioles.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] As the Terrapins' owners were not offered any part of the buyout offer made to most Federal League teams by the American and National Leagues, they decided to sue, alleging that the buyout was in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] Supreme Court deciding that the scheduling and playing of "base ball games" did not constitute "interstate commerce" in any sense envisioned by the Framers of the United States Constitution; therefore, the Sherman Act and other federal laws and regulations did not apply to baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] National League*, was not ultimately decided until 1922.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] The minor league Orioles moved into Terrapin Park, a wooden ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/baltimore-terrapins] This move began a chain of events which would eventually lead to the return of major league baseball to Baltimore.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:ducky-yount/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **earned run average** (**ERA**) is the average of earned runs allowed by a pitcher per nine innings pitched (i.e. the traditional length of a game).
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] It is determined by dividing the number of earned runs allowed by the number of innings pitched and multiplying by nine.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Runs resulting from passed balls, defensive errors (including pitchers' defensive errors), and runners placed on base at the start of extra innings are recorded as unearned runs and omitted from ERA calculations.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Henry Chadwick is credited with devising the statistic, which caught on as a measure of pitching effectiveness after relief pitching came into vogue in the 1900s.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Prior to 1900 and for many years afterward, pitchers were routinely expected to pitch a complete game, and their win–loss record was considered sufficient in determining their effectiveness.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] After pitchers like James Otis Crandall and Charley Hall made names for themselves as relief specialists, gauging a pitcher's effectiveness became more difficult using the traditional method of tabulating wins and losses.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Some criterion was needed to capture the apportionment of earned-run responsibility for a pitcher in games that saw contributions from other pitchers for the same team.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Since pitchers have primary responsibility for getting opposing batters out, they must assume responsibility when a batter they do not retire at the plate moves to base, and eventually reaches home, scoring a run.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] A pitcher is assessed an **earned run** for each run scored by a batter (or the batter's pinch-runner) who reaches base while batting against that pitcher.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The National League first tabulated official earned run average statistics in 1912 (the outcome was called "Heydler's statistic" for a while, after then-NL secretary John Heydler), and the American League later accepted this standard and began compiling ERA statistics.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Baseball encyclopedias will often display ERAs for earlier years, but these were computed retroactively.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Negro league pitchers are often rated by *RA*, or total runs allowed, since the statistics available for Negro league games did not always distinguish between earned and unearned runs.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] As with batting average, the definition of a good ERA varies from year to year.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] During the dead-ball era of the 1900s and 1910s, an ERA below 2.00 (two earned runs allowed per nine innings) was considered good.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In the late 1920s and through the 1930s, when conditions of the game changed in a way that strongly favored hitters, a good ERA was below 4.00; only the highest caliber pitchers, for example Dazzy Vance or Lefty Grove, would consistently post an ERA under 3.00 during these years.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In the 1960s, sub-2.00 ERAs returned as other influences, such as ballparks with different dimensions, were introduced.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Starting with the 2019 season, an ERA under 4.00 is again considered good.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The single-season record for the lowest ERA is held by Dutch Leonard, who in 1914 had an earned run average of 0.96, pitching 224.2 innings with a win–loss record of 19–5.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The all-time record for the lowest single season earned run average by a pitcher pitching 300 or more innings is 1.12, set by Bob Gibson in 1968.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The record for the lowest career earned run average is 1.82, held by Ed Walsh, who played from 1904 through 1917.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Some players may be listed with infinite ERAs.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] This can happen if a pitcher allows one or more earned runs without retiring a batter.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Several players have registered an infinite ERA for their limited pitching careers in MLB, usually a single appearance.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Examples include Bill Ford with the Boston Bees in 1936 and Fred Bruckbauer with the Minnesota Twins in 1961.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Outfielder Vic Davalillo made two pitching appearances with St.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Louis Cardinals in 1969 and failed to record an out while facing four batters and allowing one run, leaving him with an infinite ERA as a major-league pitcher.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] (This comes from attempting to divide any non-zero number by zero).
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] An undefined ERA occasionally occurs at the beginning of a baseball season when a pitcher has yet to appear in any games.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] It is sometimes incorrectly displayed as zero or as the lowest-ranking ERA.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] At times it can be misleading to judge relief pitchers solely on ERA, because they are charged only for runs scored by batters who reached base while batting against them.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Thus, if a relief pitcher enters the game while his team is leading by 1 run, with 2 outs and the bases loaded, and then gives up a single which scores 2 runs, he is not charged with those runs.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] If he retires the next batter (and pitches no more innings), his ERA for that game will be 0.00 despite having surrendered the lead.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] (He is recorded with a blown save if those runs tied the game or affected a lead change.) Starting pitchers operate under the same rules, but are not called upon to start pitching with runners already on base.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In addition, relief pitchers know beforehand that they will only be pitching for a relatively short while, allowing them to exert themselves more for each pitch, unlike starters who typically need to conserve their energy over the course of a game in case they are asked to pitch 7 or more innings.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The reliever's freedom to use their maximum energy for a few innings, or even for just a few batters, helps them keep their ERAs down.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] ERA, taken by itself, can also be misleading when trying to objectively judge starting pitchers, though not to the extent seen with relief pitchers.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The advent of the designated hitter rule in the American League in 1973 made the pitching environment significantly different.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Starting in 1997, when teams began playing teams from the other league during the regular season, the DH rule was in effect only when such interleague games are played in an American League park; this was rendered moot after the National League permanently adopted the DH in 2022.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] This difference between the leagues (the DH) also affected relievers, but not to the same degree.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] This is because National League relievers actually pitched to pitchers less often than NL starters did for a number of reasons, mainly because relievers are usually active in later innings when the double switch was available and/or pinch hitters tended to be used in the pitcher's batting spot.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] ERA is also affected somewhat by the ballpark where a pitcher's team plays half its games, as well as the tendency of hometown official scorers to assign errors instead of base hits in plays that could be either.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] As an extreme example, pitchers for the Colorado Rockies have historically faced many problems, all damaging to their ERAs.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] The combination of high altitude (5,280 ft or 1,610 m) and a semi-arid climate in Denver causes fly balls to travel up to 10% further than at sea level.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Denver's altitude and low humidity also diminish the ability of pitchers to throw effective breaking balls, due to both reduced air resistance and difficulty in gripping dry baseballs.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] These conditions have been countered to some extent since 2002 by the team's use of humidors to store baseballs before games.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] These difficult circumstances for Rockies pitchers may not adversely affect their win–loss records, since opposing pitchers must deal with the same problems.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Indeed, hometown hurlers have some advantage in any given game since they are physically acclimated to the altitude and often develop techniques to mitigate the challenges of this ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Still, conditions there tend to inflate Rockies' ERAs relative to the rest of the league.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In modern baseball, sabermetrics uses several defense independent pitching statistics (DIPS) including a Defense-Independent ERA in an attempt to measure a pitcher's ability regardless of factors outside his control.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] For example, this is the premise of Nate Silver's forecasts of ERAs using his PECOTA system.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Silver also developed a "quick" earned run average (QuikERA or QERA) to calculate an ERA from peripheral statistics including strikeouts, walks, and groundball percentage.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Unlike peripheral ERA or PERA, it does not take into account park effects.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] Another statistic derived from ERA is Adjusted ERA, also called ERA+, which adjusts a pitcher's ERA to a scale where 100 is average for the league and takes into account the various dimensions and other factors of each ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In baseball statistics, **runs per nine innings** (denoted by **R/9** or **RA9**) is a measure of a pitcher's effectiveness in preventing runs; calculated as: (9 × runs allowed) / (innings pitched).
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] In this way, it is different from the ERA in that all runs, rather than only earned runs, are included.
[src:ducky-yount/earned-run-average] This is a list of the lowest ERAs among pitchers that played their entire careers after 1920 (minimum 1,500 innings pitched, starting pitcher).
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League came together in early 1913 through the work of John T.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Powers, and immediately challenged the operations of organized baseball as a minor league playing outside of the National Agreement.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Gilmore succeeded Powers as league president, the league declared itself to be a major league.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Playing in what detractors called the "outlaw" league allowed players to avoid the restrictions of the organized leagues' reserve clause.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The competition of another, better paying league caused players' salaries to skyrocket, demonstrating the bargaining potential of free agency for the first time since the war between the AL and NL.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Interference by the National and American Leagues in their operations caused the Federal League to fold after the 1915 season.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] This resulted in a landmark federal lawsuit, *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Supreme Court ultimately ruled that the Sherman Antitrust Act did not apply to Major League Baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League left its mark on baseball history in the field now known as Wrigley Field, which was originally built for the Chicago Whales Federal League team.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The league itself and many sports writers considered it a major league during its existence; organized baseball recognized its major league status in 1968.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Not including the Negro Major Leagues, it would be the last independent major league outside the established structure of professional baseball to make it to the playing field, and would be the last serious attempt to create a third major league until the abortive Continental League of 1960.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Powers formed an independent professional league known as the **Columbian League**.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] However, the withdrawal of one of the organization's primary investors caused the league to fail before ever playing a game.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Undaunted, Powers tried again the following year, creating a new league with teams in Chicago, Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Indianapolis, St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] He named the organization the Federal League, and served as its first president.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Because it did not abide by the National Agreement on player payment in place in organized baseball, the Federal League was called an "outlaw league" by its competitors.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League's outlaw status allowed it to recruit players from established clubs, and it attracted many current and former players from the major as well as minor leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In 1913, the Federal League played as an independent six-team minor league.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In its first season Powers initially served as president, but he was soon replaced by James A.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Gilmore, under whose leadership the league declared itself a major league for the 1914 season.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Other financiers of the League included oil baron Harry F.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Sinclair, ice magnate Phil Ball, and George S.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] As a major circuit, the Federal League consisted of eight teams each season.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Four of the teams were placed in cities with existing major league baseball teams (Chicago, St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The other four teams were placed in areas without a current major league club (Baltimore, Buffalo, Indianapolis and Kansas City).
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In the first year, 1914, some of the teams had official nicknames and some did not, but either way, sportswriters were inclined to invent their own nicknames: "ChiFeds," "BrookFeds," etc.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In order for the Federal League to succeed, it needed Big League players.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Walter Johnson signed a three-year contract with the Chicago team, but the Senators' Clark Griffith went personally to Johnson's home in Kansas and made a successful counter-offer.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Major League players that jumped to the Federal League included Bill McKechnie, Claude Hendrix, Jack Quinn, Russell Ford, Tom Seaton, Doc Crandall, Al Bridwell, and Hal Chase.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League also recruited Big League names to manage the new teams.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Joe Tinker managed the Chicago team, Mordecai Brown managed the St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis team and Bill Bradley managed the Brooklyn team.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In 1914, the Colonial League began to operate as a Class C level league based in Southern New England.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In April, Alexander Bannwart drew notice by acquiring Big Jeff Pfeffer to manage the team in Pawtucket, Rhode Island, and by May, it was suspected that Bannwart was working as an agent of the Federal League, which Bannwart denied.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Upon these news reports, some of the founding members of the Colonial League resigned, fearing banishment by the National Baseball Commission.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] At the April 1915 league meeting, Coppen was re-elected as president and Bannwart was elected secretary.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Ward, the treasurer of the Brooklyn Tip-Tops of the Federal League and George S.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Ward's son, was elected as the league's treasurer.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Colonial League reorganized itself as a farm system for the Federal League and voluntarily withdrew itself from organized baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League had close pennant races both years.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In 1914, Indianapolis beat out Chicago by 1½ games.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] 1915 witnessed the tightest pennant race in Major League history, as three teams (Chicago, St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis and Pittsburgh) fought into the last weekend of the season.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] On the season's final day, Sunday, October 3, Chicago split a doubleheader with Pittsburgh, winning the darkness-shortened seven-inning nightcap, 3-0; this combined with St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis' 6-2 win over Kansas City, knocked Pittsburgh back to third (albeit just a half-game behind), with Chicago and St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] But since the Whales (86-66) played two fewer games than the St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis Terriers (87-67), they were awarded the pennant based on their slightly better winning percentage (.566 to .565).
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Pittsburgh, with one game unplayed, ended up at 86-67 (.562).
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] During the 1914–15 offseason, Federal League owners brought an antitrust lawsuit against the American and National Leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The lawsuit ended up in the court of Federal Judge (and future Commissioner of Baseball) Kenesaw Mountain Landis, who allowed the case to languish while he urged both sides to negotiate.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Swift action might have made a difference, but without the lawsuit going forward, the Federals found themselves in deepening financial straits.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] After the 1915 season, the owners of the American and National Leagues bought out half of the owners (Pittsburgh, Newark, Buffalo, and Brooklyn) of the Federal League teams.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Two Federal League owners were allowed to buy struggling franchises in the established leagues: Phil Ball, owner of the St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis Terriers, was allowed to buy the St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis Browns of the AL, and Charles Weeghman, owner of the Chicago Whales, bought the Chicago Cubs.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Both owners merged their teams into the established ones.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Kansas City franchise had been declared bankrupt and taken over by the league office after the close of the regular season, and the Baltimore owners rejected the offer made to them.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] They had sought to buy and move an existing franchise to their city, but were rebuffed, and sued unsuccessfully.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] One of baseball's most famous ballparks was originally built for a Federal League team: Wrigley Field, the home of the Chicago Cubs, began its long life as Weeghman Park, the home of the Chicago Whales.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Marc Okkonen, in his book on the Federal League, referred to Wrigley as a "silent monument" to the failed Federal League experiment.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Otherwise, few visible remnants were left by the short-lived Federal League.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Baltimore entry sold their facility to the Baltimore Orioles of the International League, who renamed it Oriole Park and played there for nearly 30 years before it was destroyed by fire.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Newark ballpark was also used for minor league ball for a short time.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Washington Park III in Brooklyn, completed after the 1915 season was underway, resembled Chicago's Weeghman Park.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] It was used for various sports until the end of 1917 and then for storage until Brooklyn Edison Electric bought the property in 1925 and shortly thereafter tore it down.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The other Federal League ballparks were demolished quickly, including the home of the Pittsburgh Rebels, Exposition Park, which had been the home of the Pittsburgh Pirates of the National League until they moved into Forbes Field in 1909.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The other "silent monument" to the Federal League is a famous legal decision.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In 1922, the Supreme Court ruled in *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Though significantly weakened in the 1970s, this exemption remains intact 104 years later; however, it has been eroded by subsequent court rulings and legislation regarding issues specific to Major League Baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Of the locations of teams in the Federal League, five currently have major league teams.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Those are Baltimore, Chicago, Kansas City, Pittsburgh and St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Brooklyn has a minor league team, the Brooklyn Cyclones.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Newark had a team, the Bears, in the independent Can-Am League, which folded after the 2012 season.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] There is at least one achievement of note that happened in Federal League play.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis Terriers, won his milestone 300th game on September 11, 1915, at St.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Louis' Handlan's Park, becoming the first 300-game winning left-hander in the history of major league baseball and one of only six as of 2018.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] However, that milestone was not acknowledged by Major League Baseball until 1968.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League was the last serious attempt at creating a "third major league" outside the established structure of professional baseball in the U.S.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] There was one further attempt at creating a third league – the Continental League in 1959 – but its founders had hoped to find their place within the purview of organized baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Continental League disbanded in 1960 without ever playing a game, making the Federal League the last such league to ever take to the field.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] The Federal League features prominently in Ring Lardner's sports humor book *You Know Me Al* (1916), in which the protagonist pitches for the Chicago White Sox and repeatedly threatens to jump to the Federal League whenever he feels underappreciated or underpaid.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Players in the Baseball Hall of Fame who played in the Federal League are listed below.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Each of these players was elected via the Veterans Committee.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] In addition, Cy Young managed the 1913 Cleveland Green Sox.
[src:ducky-yount/federal-league] Per final regular season standings, as there was no postseason.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Prior to colonization, three Siouan-speaking tribes associated with a culture group called the Eastern Siouans probably inhabited the area that is now Iredell County.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Broken into several smaller tribes, they were the Catawba, the Waccamaw Siouan, the Cheraw, the Winyah, the Wateree and the Sugaree.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The following list shows significant events and firsts in the history of the area that is now called Iredell County, North Carolina.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is located within the Piedmont Region of central North Carolina.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The northwestern section of the county contains the Brushy Mountains, a deeply eroded spur of the Blue Ridge Mountains far to the west.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The highest point in Iredell County, Fox Mountain, is in the Brushies; it rises to 1,760 feet.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Although the "Brushies", as they are often called locally, are not high in the normal sense, they do rise prominently above the surrounding countryside.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The remainder of Iredell County consists of gently rolling countryside occasionally broken by low hills and small river valleys.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The county's largest river, the Catawba, forms much of its western border.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Lake Norman, North Carolina's largest manmade lake, is the most prominent geographic feature of southern Iredell County; it is often called North Carolina's "inland sea".
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is an important transportation center for the state, as Interstate 77 and Interstate 40 cross in northeast Statesville.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The northern third of Iredell County is highly rural and contains no large towns.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Due to the thinly populated nature of this portion of the state, it is one of the select places in North Carolina where the speed limit on Interstate Highways exceeds 65 mph, as Interstate 77 north of Statesville has a speed limit of 70 mph.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is one of the longest counties in the state and stretches for nearly fifty miles north to south, from Yadkin County in the north to Mecklenburg County in the south.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] As of the 2020 census, there were 186,693 people and 49,635 families residing in the county.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The median age was 41.2 years, 23.0% of residents were under the age of 18, and 16.8% of residents were 65 years of age or older; for every 100 females there were 96.4 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 94.0 males age 18 and over.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] There were 72,706 households in the county, of which 32.3% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Of all households, 52.3% were married-couple households, 16.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 24.7% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] About 24.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] There were 79,372 housing units, of which 8.4% were vacant.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Among occupied housing units, 71.1% were owner-occupied and 28.9% were renter-occupied.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.4% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.0%.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 74.7% White, 11.6% Black or African American, 0.4% American Indian and Alaska Native, 2.6% Asian, less than 0.1% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 4.1% from some other race, and 6.7% from two or more races.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 8.5% of the population.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] 68.1% of residents lived in urban areas, while 31.9% lived in rural areas.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 159,437 people, and 59,593 households in the county.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The population density was 277.8 people per square mile (107.3 people/km2).
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] As of 2013 there were 69,325 housing units at an average density of 90 per square mile (35/km2).
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 83.3% White, 12.3% Black or African American, 0.5% Native American, 2.2% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander, 1.68% from other races, and 1.6% from two or more races.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] 7.0% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] According to the 2000 census data, there were 47,360 households, out of which 33.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 57.8% were married couples living together, 11.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 26.8% were non-families.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] 22.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 8.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The average household size was 2.56 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] In the county, the population was spread out, with 25.5% under the age of 18, 7.5% from 18 to 24, 31.3% from 25 to 44, 23.3% from 45 to 64, and 12.4% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] For every 100 females there were 96.1 males.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 93.1 males.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] As of 2013, the median income for a household in the county was $50,058.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Males had a median income of $34,590 versus $24,031 for females.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $26,348.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] About 6.2% of families and 13.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 10.1% of those under age 18 and 9.8% of those age 65 or over.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is governed by the Board of Commissioners, consisting of five commissioners elected at-large, which requires each to attract a majority of the votes.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Iredell County Commissioners (2016–present) are James Mallory (chairman), Marvin Norman, Tommy Bowles, Jeff McNeely and Gene Houpe, all Republicans.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is a member of the Centralina Council of Governments.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Register of Deeds of Iredell County is Ronald "Duck" Wyatt (Republican), appointed in 2016.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Register of Deeds serves as custodian and manager of a large number of land records and vital records.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is part of prosecutorial District 22A with Alexander County.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Iredell County Courthouse is located in the county seat of Statesville, North Carolina.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Senior Resident Superior Court Judge is Joe Crosswhite.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Chief District Court Judge is Dale Graham.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] James Lee (Jim) Mixson III has served as Iredell County's Clerk of Superior Court since 2012.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Clerks of Superior Court in North Carolina also serve as Probate Judges in addition to their administrative duties.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Since 1952, Iredell County voting records show a strong Republican majority.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Before 1952, however, Iredell was part of the Democratic "Solid South" and voted for no Republican presidential candidate after Reconstruction except Herbert Hoover in 1928.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] In 1964, the year that national civil rights legislation was passed, it was one of 13 North Carolina counties to vote for Barry Goldwater.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] In the past 17 elections, the only Democrat to carry Iredell County was Jimmy Carter in 1976, who was a native son of Georgia and the South.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Iredell County Sheriff's Office was founded in 1789, in the year after the county was formed from Rowan County.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The Sheriff of Iredell County is Darren E.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Campbell (Republican), elected in December 2014.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] He succeeded Phillip Redmond, who was first elected in 1994.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] One of the most famous prisoners held by Sheriff William Franklin Wasson in the Iredell County jail was Tom Dula, who was hung on May 1, 1868, in Statesville.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Farming is still a major source of income for many Iredell County residents.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Dairy farming has been particularly popular in Iredell County since the early 1800s, in both the northern and southern sections of the county.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] However, the rapid population growth and development in southern Iredell County is putting increasing pressure on farmlands, and many farms in this section are giving way to shopping centers, housing developments, and large corporate office parks.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Iredell County is a major hub of NASCAR racing, with many race shops located in the county (mostly around Mooresville).
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Universal Technical Institute operates NASCAR Technical Institute under licensing agreements.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The school offers racing-related instruction to prepare the student for their job search in the racing industry.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Many NASCAR drivers live around Mooresville and Lake Norman.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Although northern Iredell County has retained much of its rural character, the southern half of the county is experiencing rapid suburbanization and population growth, largely due to the immense popularity of the Lake Norman area for residents of nearby Charlotte, North Carolina's largest city.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Lowe's has its corporate headquarters in Mooresville.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The county is served by two traditional public school districts: Iredell-Statesville Schools (ISS) and Mooresville Graded School District (MGSD).
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] By the requirements of the North Carolina Constitution of 1868, all counties in North Carolina were divided into townships.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] Previous to that time, the subdivisions in Iredell County were Captain's Districts.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] While the Captain's Districts referred primarily to the militia, it served also for the election precinct, the tax listing and tax collecting district.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] In the 1700s and 1800s, before there were many towns in what became Iredell County, property was identified by stream, rivers, or adjacent landowners.
[src:ducky-yount/iredell-county-north-carolina] The following is a list of the streams, rivers, and creeks in Iredell County.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Formed in 1876 and 1901, respectively, the NL and AL cemented their cooperation with the National Agreement in 1903, making MLB the oldest major professional sports league in the United States and Canada.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] They remained legally separate entities until 2000, when they merged into a single organization led by the commissioner of baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's first all-professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was founded in 1869.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The first few decades of professional baseball saw rivalries between leagues, and players often jumped from one team or league to another.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] These practices were essentially ended by the National Agreement of 1903, in which AL and NL agreed to respect each other's player contracts, including the contentious reserve clause, which bound players to their teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The period from about 1900 to 1920 was the dead-ball era, when home runs were rarely hit.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Professional baseball was rocked by the Black Sox Scandal, a conspiracy to fix the 1919 World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball survived the scandal, albeit with major changes in its governance, as the relatively weak National Commission was replaced with a powerful commissioner of baseball with near-unlimited authority over the sport.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB rose in popularity in the decade following the Black Sox Scandal, and unlike major leagues in other sports, it endured the Great Depression and World War II without any of its teams folding.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Shortly after the war, Jackie Robinson broke baseball's color barrier.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Some teams moved to different cities in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The AL and NL added eight clubs in the 1960s, which started the expansion era: two in 1961, two in 1962, and four in 1969.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Player discontent with established labor practices, especially the reserve clause, led to the organization of the Major League Baseball Players Association to collectively bargain with the owners, which in turn led to the introduction of free agency in baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Modern stadiums with artificial turf surfaces began to change the game in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs began to dominate the game during the 1990s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In the mid-2000s, media reports disclosed the use of anabolic steroids among MLB players; a 2006–07 investigation produced the *Mitchell Report*, which found that many players had used steroids and other performance-enhancing substances, including at least one player from each team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is the third-wealthiest professional sports league in the world by revenue after the National Football League (NFL) and the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball games are broadcast on television, radio, and the internet throughout North America and in several other countries.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has the highest total season attendance of any sports league in the world; in 2025, it drew 71.4 million spectators.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also oversees Minor League Baseball, which comprises lower-tier teams affiliated with the major league clubs, the MLB Draft League, a hybrid amateur-professional showcase league, and the Arizona Fall League, an off-season showcase league for minor league players.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB and the World Baseball Softball Confederation jointly manage the international World Baseball Classic tournament.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Yankees have the most championships with 27.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The reigning champions are the Los Angeles Dodgers, who defeated the Toronto Blue Jays in the 2025 World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1860s, aided by soldiers playing the game in camp during the Civil War, "New York"-style baseball expanded into a national game and spawned baseball's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP existed as an amateur league for 12 years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1867, more than 400 clubs were members.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Most of the strongest clubs remained those based in the northeastern United States.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] For professional baseball's founding year, MLB uses the year 1869—when the first professional team, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, was established.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] A schism developed between professional and amateur ballplayers after the founding of the Cincinnati club.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The NABBP split into an amateur organization and a professional organization.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The National Association of Professional Base Ball Players, often known as the National Association (NA), was formed in 1871.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Its amateur counterpart disappeared after only a few years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The modern Chicago Cubs and Atlanta Braves franchises trace their histories back to the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in the 1870s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1876, the National League of Professional Base Ball Clubs (later known as the National League or NL) was established after the NA proved ineffective.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The league placed its emphasis on clubs rather than on players.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs could now enforce player contracts, preventing players from jumping to higher-paying clubs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Clubs were required to play the full schedule of games instead of forfeiting scheduled games when the club was no longer in the running for the league championship, which happened frequently under the NA.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] A concerted effort was made to curb gambling on games, which was leaving the validity of results in doubt.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The first game in the NL—on Saturday, April 22, 1876 (at Jefferson Street Grounds in Philadelphia)—is often pointed to as the beginning of MLB.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The early years of the NL were tumultuous, with threats from rival leagues and a rebellion by players against the hated "reserve clause", which restricted the free movement of players between clubs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams came and went; 1882 was the first season where the league's membership was the same as the preceding season's, and only four franchises survived to see 1900.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Competitor leagues formed regularly and also disbanded regularly.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The most successful was the American Association (1882–1891), sometimes called the "beer and whiskey league" for its tolerance of the sale of alcoholic beverages to spectators.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] For several years, the NL and American Association champions met in a postseason championship series—the first attempt at a World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The two leagues merged in 1892 as a single 12-team NL, but the NL dropped four teams after the 1899 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This led to the formation of the American League (AL) in 1901 under president Ban Johnson, and the resulting bidding war for players led to widespread contract-breaking and legal disputes.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The war between the AL and NL sent shockwaves throughout the baseball world.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] At a meeting at the Leland Hotel in Chicago in 1901, the other baseball leagues negotiated a plan to maintain their independence.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] A new National Association was formed to oversee these minor leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After 1902, the NL, AL, and NA signed a new National Agreement, which tied independent contracts to the reserve-clause contracts.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The agreement also set up a formal classification system for minor leagues, the forerunner of today's system that was refined by Branch Rickey.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Several other early defunct baseball leagues are considered major leagues, and their statistics and records are included with those of the two modern major leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball officially recognized six major leagues: the National League, American League, American Association, Union Association (1884), Players' League (1890), and Federal League (1914–1915).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The status of the National Association as a major league has been a point of dispute among baseball researchers; while its statistics are not recognized by Major League Baseball, its statistics *are* included with those of other major leagues by some baseball reference websites, such as Retrosheet.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Some researchers, including Nate Silver, dispute the major-league status of the Union Association by pointing out that franchises came and went and that the St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was deliberately "stacked"; the St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis club was owned by the league's president and it was the only club that was close to major-league caliber.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2021, baseball reference website Baseball-Reference.com began to include statistics from those seven leagues into their major-league statistics.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The period between 1900 and 1919 is commonly referred to as the "dead-ball era".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Games of this era tended to be low-scoring and were often dominated by pitchers, such as Walter Johnson, Cy Young, Christy Mathewson, Mordecai Brown, and Grover Cleveland Alexander.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The term also accurately describes the condition of the baseball itself.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The baseball used American rather than the modern Australian wool yarn and was not wound as tightly, affecting the distance that it would travel.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] More significantly, balls were kept in play until they were mangled, soft and sometimes lopsided.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] During this era, a baseball cost $3, (equivalent to $56 in 2025), and owners were reluctant to purchase new balls.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Fans were expected to throw back fouls and (rare) home runs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseballs also became stained with tobacco juice, grass, and mud, and sometimes the juice of licorice, which some players would chew for the purpose of discoloring the ball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Also, pitchers could manipulate the ball through the use of the spitball (In 1921, use of this pitch was restricted to a few pitchers with a grandfather clause).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Hitting methods like the Baltimore chop were used to increase the number of infield singles.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] On a successful Baltimore chop, the batter hits the ball forcefully into the ground, causing it to bounce so high that the batter reaches first base before the ball can be fielded and thrown to the first baseman.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The adoption of the foul strike rule—in the NL in 1901, in the AL two years later—quickly sent baseball from a high-scoring game to one where scoring runs became a struggle.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Before this rule, foul balls were not counted as strikes: a batter could foul off any number of pitches with no strikes counted against him; this gave an enormous advantage to the batter.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 1919 World Series between the Chicago White Sox and Cincinnati Reds, baseball was rocked by allegations of a game-fixing scheme known as the Black Sox Scandal.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Eight players—"Shoeless" Joe Jackson, Eddie Cicotte, Claude "Lefty" Williams, George "Buck" Weaver, Arnold "Chick" Gandil, Fred McMullin, Charles "Swede" Risberg, and Oscar "Happy" Felsch—intentionally lost the World Series in exchange for a ring worth $100,000 (equivalent to $1,860,000 in 2025).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Despite being acquitted, all were permanently banned from MLB.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball's popularity increased in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1920 season was notable for the death of Ray Chapman of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Chapman, who was struck in the head by a pitch and died a few hours later, became the only MLB player to die of an on-field injury.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Both leagues quickly began to require the use of new, white baseballs whenever a ball became scuffed or dirty, helping bring the "dead-ball" era to an end.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the New York Yankees made their first World Series appearance.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 1930s, the team had appeared in 11 World Series, winning eight of them.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Yankees slugger Babe Ruth had set the single-season home run record in 1927, hitting 60 home runs; breaking his own record of 29 home runs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Impacted negatively by the Great Depression, baseball's popularity had begun a downward turn in the early 1930s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1932, only two MLB teams turned a profit.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Attendance had fallen, due at least in part to a 10% federal amusement tax added to baseball ticket prices.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball owners cut their rosters from 25 men to 23, and even the best players took pay cuts.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Team executives were innovative in their attempts to survive, creating night games, broadcasting games live by radio, and rolling out promotions such as free admission for women.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the Great Depression, no MLB teams moved or folded.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The onset of World War II created a shortage of professional baseball players, as more than 500 men left MLB teams to serve in the military.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Many of them played on service baseball teams that entertained military personnel in the US or in the Pacific.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB teams of this time largely consisted of young men, older players, and those with a military classification of 4F, indicating mental, physical, or moral unsuitability for service.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Men like Pete Gray, a one-armed outfielder, got the chance to advance to the major leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] However, MLB rosters did not include any black players through the end of the war.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Black players, many of whom served in the war, were still restricted to playing Negro league baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Wartime blackout restrictions, designed to keep outdoor lighting at low levels, caused another problem for baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] These rules limited traveling and night games to the point that the 1942 season was nearly canceled.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] On January 14, 1942, MLB commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis wrote to U.S. president Franklin D.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt, pleading for the continuation of baseball during the war.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Roosevelt responded, "I honestly feel that it would be best for the country to keep baseball going.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] There will be fewer people unemployed and everybody will work longer hours and harder than ever before.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] With President Roosevelt's approval, spring training began in 1942 with few repercussions.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The war interrupted the careers of stars including Stan Musial, Bob Feller, Ted Williams, and Joe DiMaggio, but baseball clubs continued to field their teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Branch Rickey, president and general manager of the Brooklyn Dodgers, began making efforts to introduce a black baseball player to the previously all-white professional baseball leagues in the mid-1940s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] He selected Jackie Robinson from a list of promising Negro league players.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After obtaining a commitment from Robinson to "turn the other cheek" to any racial antagonism directed at him, Rickey agreed to sign him to a contract for $600 a month (equivalent to $9,906 in 2025).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In what was later referred to as "The Noble Experiment", Robinson was the first black baseball player in the International League since the 1880s, joining the Dodgers' farm club, the Montreal Royals, for the 1946 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The following year, the Dodgers called up Robinson to the major leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] On April 15, 1947, Robinson made his major league debut at Ebbets Field before a crowd of 26,623 spectators, including more than 14,000 black patrons.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Black baseball fans began flocking to see the Dodgers when they came to town, abandoning the Negro league teams that they had followed exclusively.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson's promotion met a generally positive, although mixed, reception among newspaper writers and white major league players.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Manager Leo Durocher informed his team, "I don't care if he is yellow or black or has stripes like a fucking zebra.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After a strike threat by some players, NL president Ford C.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick and Commissioner Happy Chandler let it be known that any striking players would be suspended.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Robinson received significant encouragement from several major-league players, including Dodgers teammate Pee Wee Reese who said, "You can hate a man for many reasons.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Color is not one of them." That year, Robinson won the inaugural Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award (separate NL and AL Rookie of the Year honors were not awarded until 1949).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Less than three months later, Larry Doby became the first African-American to break the color barrier in the American League with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The next year, a number of other black players entered the major leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Satchel Paige was signed by the Indians and the Dodgers added star catcher Roy Campanella and Don Newcombe, who was later the first winner of the Cy Young Award for his outstanding pitching.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB banned the signing of women to contracts in 1952, but that ban was lifted in 1992.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] There have been no female MLB players since then.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1903 to 1952, the major leagues consisted of two eight-team leagues whose 16 teams were located in ten cities, all in the northeastern and mid-western United States: New York City had three teams and Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia, and St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis was the southernmost and westernmost city with a major league team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The longest possible road trip, from Boston to St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After a half-century of stability, starting in the 1950s, teams began to move out of cities with multiple teams into cities that had not had them before.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1953 to 1955, three teams moved to new cities: the Boston Braves became the Milwaukee Braves, the St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Browns became the Baltimore Orioles, and the Philadelphia Athletics became the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1958 season began to turn Major League Baseball into a nationwide league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Walter O'Malley, owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers and "perhaps the most influential owner of baseball's early expansion era", moved his team to Los Angeles, marking the first major league franchise on the West Coast.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] O'Malley also helped persuade the rival New York Giants to move west to become the San Francisco Giants.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Giants owner Horace Stoneham had been contemplating a move to Minnesota amid slumping attendance at the aging Polo Grounds ballpark when O'Malley invited him to meet San Francisco mayor George Christopher in New York.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After Stoneham was persuaded to move to California, *Time* magazine put O'Malley on its cover.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Frick had opposed the meeting, but the dual moves proved successful for both franchises and for MLB.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Had the Dodgers moved out west alone, the St.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals—1,600 mi (2,575 km) away—would have been the closest NL team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Instead, the joint move made West Coast road trips economical for visiting teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Dodgers set a single-game MLB attendance record in their first home appearance with 78,672 fans.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1961, the first Washington Senators franchise moved to Minneapolis–Saint Paul to become the Minnesota Twins.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Two new teams were added to the American League at the same time: the Los Angeles Angels (who soon moved from downtown L.A. to nearby Anaheim) and a new Washington Senators franchise.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the Houston Astros and the New York Mets in 1962.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros (known as the "Colt .45s" during their first three seasons) became the first southern major league franchise since the Louisville Colonels folded in 1899 and the first franchise to be located along the Gulf Coast.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1966, the major leagues moved to the "Deep South" when the Milwaukee Braves moved to Atlanta.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968, the Kansas City Athletics moved west to become the Oakland Athletics.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1969, the American and National Leagues both added two expansion franchises.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The American League added the Seattle Pilots (who became the Milwaukee Brewers after one disastrous season in Seattle) and the Kansas City Royals.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The NL added the first Canadian franchise, the Montreal Expos, as well as the San Diego Padres.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1972, the second Washington Senators moved to the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex to become the Texas Rangers.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1977, baseball expanded again, adding a second Canadian team, the Toronto Blue Jays, as well as the Seattle Mariners.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Subsequently, no new teams were added until 1993, and no teams moved until 2005.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By the late 1960s, the balance between pitching and hitting had swung in favor of the pitchers.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1968—later nicknamed "the year of the pitcher"—Boston Red Sox player Carl Yastrzemski won the American League batting title with an average of just .301, the lowest in MLB history.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Detroit Tigers pitcher Denny McLain won 31 games, making him the only pitcher to win 30 games in a season since Dizzy Dean in 1934.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals starting pitcher Bob Gibson achieved an equally remarkable feat by allowing an ERA of just 1.12.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Following these pitching performances, in December 1968 the MLB Playing Rules Committee voted to reduce the strike zone from knees to shoulders to top of knees to armpits and lower the pitcher's mound from 15 to 10 inches, beginning in the 1969 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1973, the American League, which had been suffering from much lower attendance than the National League, sought to increase scoring even further by initiating the designated hitter (DH) rule.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Throughout the 1960s and 1970s, as baseball expanded, the National Football League (NFL) had been surging in popularity, making it economical for many of these cities to build multi-purpose stadiums instead of single-purpose baseball fields.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Because of climate and economic issues, many of these facilities had playing surfaces made from artificial turf, as well as the oval designs characteristic of stadiums designed to house both baseball and football.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This often resulted in baseball fields with relatively more foul territory than older stadiums.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] These characteristics changed the nature of professional baseball, putting a higher premium on speed and defense over home-run hitting power since the fields were often too big for teams to expect to hit many home runs and foul balls hit in the air could more easily be caught for outs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Teams began to be built around pitching—particularly their bullpens—and speed on the basepaths.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Artificial surfaces meant balls traveled quicker and bounced higher, so it became easier to hit ground balls "in the hole" between the corner and middle infielders.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Starting pitchers were no longer expected to throw complete games; it was enough for a starter to pitch 6–7 innings and turn the game over to the team's closer, a position which grew in importance over these decades.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] As stolen bases increased, home run totals dropped.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After Willie Mays hit 52 home runs in 1965, only one player (George Foster) reached that mark until the 1990s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] During the 1980s, baseball experienced a number of significant changes the game had not seen in years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Home runs were on the decline throughout the decade, with players hitting 40 home runs just 13 times and no one hitting more than 50 home runs in a season for the first time since the dead-ball era (1900–1919).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1981 MLB strike from June 12 until July 31 forced the cancellation of 713 games and resulted in a split-season format.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1985, Pete Rose broke Ty Cobb's all-time hits record with his 4,192nd hit.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1989, Rose received a lifetime ban from baseball as a result of betting on baseball games while manager of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Rose was the first person to receive a lifetime ban from baseball since 1943.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] 1985 also saw the Pittsburgh drug trials which involved players who were called to testify before a grand jury in Pittsburgh related to cocaine trafficking.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The 1994–95 MLB strike from August 12, 1994, to April 25, 1995, caused the cancellation of over 900 games and the forfeit of the entire 1994 postseason.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Routinely in the late 1990s and early 2000s, baseball players hit 40 or 50 home runs in a season, a feat that was considered rare even in the 1980s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] It later became apparent that at least some of this power surge was a result of players using steroids and other performance-enhancing drugs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League added the Florida Marlins in Miami and the Colorado Rockies in Denver.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1998, the Brewers switched leagues by joining the National League, and two new teams were added: the National League's Arizona Diamondbacks in Phoenix and the American League's Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] After the 2001 season, the team owners voted in favor of contraction.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Several MLB teams had been considered for elimination in early talks about contraction, but the Montreal Expos and the Minnesota Twins were the two teams that came closest to folding under the plan.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Plans for MLB contraction were halted when the Twins landlord was awarded a court injunction that required the team to play its 2002 home games at their stadium.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB owners agreed to hold off on reducing the league's size until at least 2006.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Montreal Expos became the first franchise in over three decades to move when they became the Washington Nationals in 2005.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This move left Canada with just one team, but it also returned baseball to Washington after a 33-year absence.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This franchise shift, like many previous ones, involved baseball's return to a city that had been previously abandoned.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In recent years, with the advent of technologies such as Statcast and its use of Hawk-Eye starting in 2020 as well as with advanced statistics as provided by sites such as FanGraphs and Baseball Savant, MLB has evolved.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] With the ability to see precise movements of pitchers and batters, teams can assess the mechanics of a player and help them improve.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast also provides some features such as tracking the paths of most batted balls, tracking the speed of most batted balls, and tracking the exit velocity of most batted balls.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Statcast has allowed for advanced defensive analytics that have not been possible before tracking of players due to how subjective fielding can be.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The rate of teams using a defensive shift went up from 13.7% in 2016 to 33.6% in 2022 because advanced statistics supported this as an effective way to stop hitters from getting hits.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Because the shift reduces the number of balls in play that result in hits and MLB wishes to increase interest in baseball, MLB announced in September 2022 that extreme infield defensive shifts would be banned starting in 2023.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] To be compliant, there must be two fielders on each side of second base, and those fielders must have both of their feet on the infield dirt at the time the pitch is thrown.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] If this rule is not followed, the choice of an automatic ball or the outcome of the play is given to the batting team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The game of baseball has also slowed down significantly due to an increased number of strikeouts and walks—two outcomes that generally take many pitches to complete—and an increased amount of time taken for a pitcher to pitch.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, it took an average of three hours and six minutes to complete a 9 inning game, a number which has steadily ticked up for years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Along with the restrictions on defensive shifts, MLB announced the introduction of a pitch clock for the 2023 season and beyond, which is something that has been an experiment in MiLB for a few years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By the time the clock reaches 10 seconds, the catcher must be in their crouch behind home plate.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] When the clock reaches 8 seconds, the batter must be in the batter's box and be "alert".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Before the 15 second timer reaches 0 seconds, the pitcher must have started their "motion to pitch".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] If any of these deadlines are violated, the count of the batter will be increased by one ball if the defending team violated the pitch clock or one strike if it is the offensive team who violated the pitch clock.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Additionally, in order to prevent circumventing these rules, pickoffs and step-offs — which reset the pitch clock — are only allowed two times total per plate appearance, and if a pitcher attempts a third pickoff and fails to get the runner out, a ball will be called.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Similarly, a batter is restricted to calling a timeout (an action which resets the pitch clock) just once per plate appearance.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2019, MLB opened an investigation into allegations that members of the 2017 World Series champion Houston Astros stole signs from opposing teams using technology during the 2017 and 2018 seasons.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were found guilty in January 2020 and while no active players faced any repercussions due to an immunity agreement in exchange for testimony, Astros general manager Jeff Luhnow and field manager A.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Hinch were suspended for the entire 2020 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Astros were fined the maximum allowable $5 million and forfeited their first- and second-round picks in the 2020 and 2021 drafts.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Boston Red Sox were also found guilty of stealing signs during the 2017 and 2018 seasons, with the latter season ending in a World Series victory.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Red Sox manager Alex Cora was suspended for a year and the team was fined with the loss of a second-round draft pick in the 2020 draft as a result.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In November 2023, the Oakland Athletics relocation to Las Vegas was approved by MLB owners.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] They are to play the 2025 through 2027 seasons in West Sacramento, California, while a new stadium is built in the Las Vegas metropolitan area, and will be referred to as simply the "Athletics" and "A's", with no city name attached.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB has discussed preparations for another round of expansion, and several investment groups are vying for a franchise.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred said MLB could add two teams and pursue a geographic realignment of its leagues and divisions.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB is governed by the Major League Baseball Constitution.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This document has undergone several incarnations since its creation in 1876.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the direction of the commissioner of baseball, MLB hires and maintains the sport's umpiring crews, and negotiates marketing, labor, and television contracts.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB maintains a unique, controlling relationship over the sport, including most aspects of Minor League Baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This is due in large part to the 1922 U.S.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Supreme Court ruling in *Federal Baseball Club v.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] National League*, which held that baseball is not interstate commerce and therefore not subject to federal antitrust law; MLB is the only league that has such a status, and has not faced any competition since this case.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This ruling has been weakened only slightly in subsequent years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The weakened ruling granted more stability to the owners of teams and has resulted in values increasing at double-digit rates.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] There were several challenges to MLB's primacy in the sport, with notable attempts to establish competing leagues occurring during the late 1800s, from 1913 to 1915 with the short-lived Federal League, and in 1960 with the aborted Continental League.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The chief executive of MLB is the commissioner, Rob Manfred.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The deputy commissioner of baseball administration and chief legal officer is Dan Halem.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The multimedia branch of MLB is MLB Advanced Media, which is based in New York City.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This branch oversees MLB.com and each of the 30 teams' websites.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Its charter states that MLB Advanced Media holds editorial independence from the league, but it is under the same ownership group and revenue-sharing plan.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB Productions is a similarly structured wing of the league, focusing on video and traditional broadcast media.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB also owns 67 percent of MLB Network, with the other 33 percent split between several cable operators and satellite provider DirecTV.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] It operates out of studios in Secaucus, New Jersey, and also has editorial independence from the league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1920, the weak National Commission, created to manage relationships between the two leagues, was replaced with the much more powerful commissioner of baseball, who had the power to make decisions for all of professional baseball unilaterally.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1901 to 1960, the American League and National League fielded eight teams apiece.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In the 1960s, MLB expansion added eight teams, including the first non-U.S. team (the Montreal Expos).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Two teams (the Seattle Mariners and the Toronto Blue Jays) were also added in the 1970s.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] From 1969 through 1993, each league consisted of an East and West Division.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 1993, the National League expanded with two teams, the Florida Marlins and the Colorado Rockies, to even up the number of teams in both leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] A third division, the Central Division, was formed in each league in 1994.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Until 1996, the two leagues met on the field only during the World Series and the All-Star Game.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In March 1995, two new franchises, the Arizona Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay Devil Rays (now known as the Tampa Bay Rays), were awarded by MLB, which began play in 1998.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This addition brought the total number of franchises to 30.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In early 1997, MLB decided to assign one new team to each league: Tampa Bay joined the AL and Arizona joined the NL.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The original plan was to have an odd number of teams in each league (15 per league, with five in each division), but in order for every team to be able to play daily, this would have required interleague play to be scheduled throughout the entire season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] However, it was unclear at the time if the interleague play would continue after the 1998 season, as it had to be approved by the players' union.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] For this and other reasons, it was decided that both leagues should continue to have an even number of teams, and therefore, one existing club would have to switch leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed in November 1997 to move from the AL to the NL, thereby making the AL a 14-team league and the NL a 16-team league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers agreed to move from the AL East to the AL Central (to replace Milwaukee), with the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays joining the AL East.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Later, when the Houston Astros changed ownership prior to the 2013 season, the team moved from the NL Central to the AL West, resulting in both leagues having three divisions of five teams each and allowing all teams to have a more balanced schedule.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Interleague play is now held throughout the season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2000, the AL and NL were dissolved as legal entities, and MLB became a single, overall league *de jure*, similar to the National Football League (NFL), National Basketball Association (NBA) and National Hockey League (NHL)—albeit with two components called "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The use of "major-league baseball" to refer to the overall AL–NL construct prior to 2000 is preferred, since statements such as "In 1942, Ted Williams led MLB with 36 homers, 137 RBIs, a .356 batting average, and won the first of his two Triple Crowns" are anachronistic.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Since becoming a single entity, common rules and regulations have been used in both MLB leagues, with one former exception: the AL continued operating under the designated hitter (DH) rule, while the NL did not.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In 2020, the NL used the DH rule for the first time.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] As part of the settlement of the 2021–22 Major League Baseball lockout, this change was made permanent, thus making the rules in the two leagues identical.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] A baseball uniform is a type of uniform worn by baseball players and by some non-playing personnel, such as field managers and coaches.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] It is worn to indicate the person's role in the game and—through the use of logos, colors, and numbers—to identify the teams and their players, managers, and coaches.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Traditionally, home uniforms display the team name on the front, while away uniforms display the team's home location.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In modern times, however, exceptions to this pattern have become common, with teams using their team name on both uniforms.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Most teams also have one or more alternate uniforms, usually consisting of the primary or secondary team color on the vest instead of the usual white or gray.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In the past few decades throwback uniforms have become popular.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] The New York Knickerbockers were the first baseball team to use uniforms, taking the field on April 4, 1849, in pants made of blue wool, white flannel shirts (jerseys) and straw hats.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Caps and other types of headgear have been a part of baseball uniforms from the beginning.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Baseball teams often wore full-brimmed straw hats or no cap at all since there was no official rule regarding headgear.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] Under the 1882 uniform rules, players on the same team wore uniforms of different colors and patterns that indicated which position they played.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] This rule was soon abandoned as impractical.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In the late 1880s, Detroit and Washington of the National League and Brooklyn of the American Association were the first to wear striped uniforms.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By the end of the 19th century, teams began the practice of having two different uniforms, one for when they played at home in their own baseball stadium and a different one for when they played away (on the road) at the other team's ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] It became common to wear white pants with a white color vest at home and gray pants with a gray or solid (dark) colored vest when away.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] By 1900, both home and away uniforms were standard across the major leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] In June 2021, MLB announced a long-term deal with cryptocurrency exchange FTX, which includes the FTX logo appearing on umpire uniforms during all games.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] FTX is MLB's first-ever umpire uniform patch partner.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] On November 11, 2022, FTX filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p01] MLB removed the FTX patches from umpires' uniforms before the 2023 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training is a series of practices and exhibition games preceding the start of the regular season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams hold training camps in the states of Arizona and Florida, where the early warm weather allows teams to practice and play without worrying about the late winter cold.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training allows new players to compete for roster and position spots and gives existing team players practice time prior to competitive play.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams that hold spring training in Arizona are grouped into the Cactus League, while teams that hold camp in Florida are known as the Grapefruit League.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Spring training typically lasts almost two months, starting in mid-February and running until just before the season-opening day, traditionally the first week of April.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] As pitchers benefit from a longer training period, pitchers and catchers begin spring training several days before the rest of the team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] A team's schedule is typically organized into three-game series, sets of consecutive games against the same opponent, with occasional two- or four-game series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Postponed games or continuations of suspended games can result in an ad hoc one-game or five-game series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] All games of a series are usually hosted by the same team, and multiple series are typically grouped together.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] I.e, a team usually hosts several series in a row, called a homestand, and follows that by going on several road series in a row.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams generally play games five to seven days per week.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Most games are scheduled at night, although teams will often play day games on Opening Day, holidays, and for the last game of a series to allow teams extra time to travel to their next opponent.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Sunday games are generally played during the afternoon, allowing teams to travel to their next destination prior to a Monday night game.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the current three-division structure, each team plays 13 games against each of its four divisional opponents.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It plays one home series and one away series, amounting to six or seven games, against the 10 other teams in its league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] A team also plays 3-game series with all the other teams in the other league, alternating home teams each year.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Furthermore, each team has an interleague "natural rival" (in some cases its counterpart in the same metro area) with which it plays three home games and three away games each year.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] With an odd number of teams in each league (15), it is necessary to have two teams participate in interleague play for most days in the season, except when two or more teams have a day off.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2013 to 2022, each team played 20 interleague games throughout the season, usually with just one interleague game per day, but for one weekend in late May, all teams would participate in an interleague series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] (Season-long interleague play was not necessary before 2013 as each league had an even number of teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2013, the Houston Astros moved to the American League, so that each league would have 15 teams.) Prior to the adoption of the universal designated hitter in 2022, whether the DH was in use depended on whether the home team was from the AL, where the DH was used, or the NL, where it was not.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, the scheduling formula changed, with each team playing at least one series against every other team every year.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning with the 2022 season, teams compete for the six playoff berths in their respective leagues.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] To secure a berth, a team must either win its division or capture a wild card spot by having one of the three best records among the non-winners in its entire league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] With the adoption of a third wild card, the former practice of breaking ties with an additional regular-season game, known as Game 163, was dropped in favor of a tie-breaker formula.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In early-to-mid July, just after the midway point of the season, the Major League Baseball All-Star Game is held during a four-day break from the regular-season schedule.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The All-Star Game features a team of players from the American League (AL)—led by the manager of the previous AL World Series team—and a team of players from the National League (NL), similarly managed, in an exhibition game.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1959 to 1962, two games were held each season, one was held in July and one was held in August.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The designated-hitter rule was used in the All-Star Game for the first time in 1989.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Following games used a DH when the game was played in an AL ballpark.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2010, the DH rule has been in effect regardless of venue.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The first official All-Star Game was held as part of the 1933 World's Fair in Chicago, Illinois, and was the idea of Arch Ward, then sports editor for *The Chicago Tribune*.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Initially intended to be a one-time event, its great success resulted in making the game an annual one.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Ward's contribution was recognized by Major League Baseball in 1962 with the creation of the "Arch Ward Trophy", given to the All-Star Game's Most Valuable Player each year.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] (In 1970, it was renamed the Commissioner's Trophy, until 1985, when the name change was reversed.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Beginning in 1947, the eight position players in each team's starting lineup have been voted into the game by fans.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The fan voting was discontinued after a 1957 ballot-box-stuffing scandal in Cincinnati: seven of the eight slots originally went to Reds players, two of whom were subsequently removed from the lineup to make room for Willie Mays and Hank Aaron.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Fan voting was reinstated in 1970 and has continued ever since, including internet voting in recent years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2002 contest in Milwaukee controversially ended in an 11-inning tie when both managers ran out of pitchers.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In response, starting in 2003 the league which wins the All-Star game received home-field advantage in the World Series: the league champion hosted the first two games at its own ballpark as well as the last two (if necessary).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The National League did not win an All-Star game and thus gain a home-field advantage until 2010; it was able to overcome this disadvantage and win in three of the seven World Series from 2003 to 2009.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] This was discontinued after the 2016 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB All-Stars from both leagues have worn uniforms from their respective teams at the game with one exception.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 1933 All-Star Game, the National League All-Star Team members wore special gray uniforms with "National League" written in navy blue letters across the front of the jersey.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The regular season ends after the first Sunday in October (or the last Sunday in September), after which twelve teams enter the postseason playoffs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] These twelve teams consist of the six division champions and six "wild-card" teams: the team with the best overall win–loss record in each of the six divisions, and the three teams in each league with the best records other than the division champions.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Division Series and National League Division Series, each a best-of-five-games series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] American League Championship Series and National League Championship Series, each a best-of-seven-games series played between the winning teams from the Division Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The league champions are referred to as the pennant winners.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] World Series, a best-of-seven-games series played between the pennant winners of each league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Within each league, the division winners are the 1, 2, and 3-seeds, based on win–loss records.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams with the first, second, and third best records among non-division winners will be seeded 4, 5, and 6 respectively.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Throughout the postseason, home-field advantage is awarded to the team with the higher win-loss record, with tiebreakers being applied if necessary.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Wild Card Series, the 3-seed will host the 6-seed, and the 4-seed will host the 5-seed, with the winners advancing to the Division Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Unlike the NFL, there is no reseeding between each series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Division Series, the 1-seed goes up against the 4/5-seed and the 2-seed goes up against the 3/6-seed.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The winners of those matches will compete in their respective League Championship Series for their league pennant, and the pennant winners will advance to the World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2017, home-field advantage in the World Series is determined by regular-season records of the two league champions, replacing a system used for the prior 14 seasons where the champion of the league that won the All-Star Game would receive home-field advantage.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] With this format, the home-field advantage does not usually play a large role in the postseason unless the series goes to its maximum number of games.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] However, because the first two games of a postseason series are hosted by the same team, a team starting with two wins will likely have momentum heading into the venue switch.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] From 1986 to 2018, an MLB All-Star team was sent to a biennial end-of-the-season tour of Japan, dubbed the MLB Japan All-Star Series, playing exhibition games in a best-of format against the All-Stars from Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB) or, in 2014 and 2018, their national team, Samurai Japan.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB played the MLB China Series in the People's Republic of China.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of two spring-training games between the San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The games were an effort to popularize baseball in China.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB played the MLB Taiwan All-Star Series in Taiwan in November 2011.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It was a series of five exhibition games played by a team made up of MLB players called the MLB All-Stars and the Chinese Taipei national baseball team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The MLB All-Stars swept the series, five games to zero.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] At the end of the 2011 season, it was announced that the Seattle Mariners and the Oakland Athletics would play their season openers in Japan.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In October 2013, Phil Rogers of the *Chicago Tribune* wrote that MLB was considering postseason all-star tours in Taiwan and Korea; baseball is increasing in popularity in both countries.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The Arizona Diamondbacks opened the 2014 season against Los Angeles Dodgers from March 22–23 in Australia.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The teams played each other at the historic Sydney Cricket Ground, which has a seating capacity of 46,000.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The two games represented the first MLB regular-season play held in that country.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The games counted as home games for the Diamondbacks, so they played 79 home games at Chase Field.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2019, the Boston Red Sox were the home team in a regular-season two-game series against the New York Yankees.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The games, which were the first regular-season MLB games held in Europe, were played on June 29–30 at London Stadium with the Yankees winning both games.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The San Diego Padres and Los Angeles Dodgers opened the 2024 regular season on March 20–21 at Gocheok Sky Dome in Seoul, South Korea.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The ceremonial first pitch of the opening game was thrown by the first Korean-born MLB player Chan Ho Park, who made his debut with the LA Dodgers in 1994.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The two-game Seoul Series resulted in a split between the two teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] There were also four exhibition games played during March 17–18, where the Dodgers took on the Kiwoom Heroes and Team Korea, and the Padres faced the LG Twins and Team Korea.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The 2025 season began with the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Chicago Cubs playing in Tokyo at the Tokyo Dome for the MLB Tokyo Series 2025.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Together with the World Baseball Softball Confederation, MLB sponsors the World Baseball Classic, an international baseball tournament contested by national teams.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, both Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa hit more home runs than the record of 61 set by Yankees right fielder Roger Maris in 1961.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Barry Bonds topped the record in 2001 with 73 home runs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire, Bonds, and Sosa became the subjects of speculation regarding the use of performance-enhancing substances.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] McGwire later admitted that he used a steroid hormone that was still legal in baseball during the 1998 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Baseball's original steroid testing policy, in effect from 2002 to 2005, provided for penalties ranging from a ten-game suspension for a first positive test to a one-year suspension for a fourth positive test.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Players were tested at least once per year, with the chance that several players could be tested many times per year.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell was appointed by Selig on March 30, 2006 to investigate the use of performance-enhancing drugs in MLB.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The appointment was made after several influential members of the U.S.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Congress made negative comments about both the effectiveness and honesty of MLB's drug policies and Commissioner Selig.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It pointed out that HGH is likely a placebo with no performance-enhancing effects.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The report included substance use allegations against at least one player from each MLB team.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] According to ESPN, some people questioned whether Mitchell's director role with the Boston Red Sox created a conflict of interest, especially because no "prime [Sox] players were in the report".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The report named several prominent Yankees who were parts of World Series clubs; there is a long-running and fierce Yankees–Red Sox rivalry.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Dowd brought up Mitchell's conflict of interest, but he later said that the former senator had done a good job.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Mitchell acknowledged that his "tight relationship with Major League Baseball left him open to criticism", but he said that readers who examine the report closely "will not find any evidence of bias, of special treatment of the Red Sox".
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] On January 10, 2013, MLB and the players union reached an agreement to add random, in-season HGH testing.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] They also agreed to implement a new test to reveal the use of testosterone for the 2013 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The current MLB drug policy provides for an 80-game suspension for a first positive test, a 162-game suspension for a second positive test, and a lifetime suspension for a third positive test.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2009, allegations surfaced against Alex Rodriguez and David Ortiz, and Manny Ramirez received a 50-game suspension after testing positive for banned substances.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In early April 2011, Ramirez retired from baseball rather than face a 100-game suspension for his second positive steroid test.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] He would later unretire, having the suspension dropped to 50 games, and would serve those in 2012.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting in 2026, Fox, ESPN, NBC, TBS, and MLB Network will nationally televise MLB games in the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox has been MLB's primary broadcast television partner since 1996.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2008, Fox has broadcast MLB games on Saturdays throughout the entire season; Fox previously only broadcast games from May to September.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also holds rights to the All-Star Game each season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox also alternates League Championship Series broadcasts, broadcasting the American League Championship Series (ALCS) in odd-numbered years and the National League Championship Series (NLCS) in even-numbered years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Fox broadcasts all games of the World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN has been MLB's cable television partner since 1990.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The network has aired the weekly regular season game *Sunday Night Baseball* and postseason broadcasts of the Wild Card Series exclusively.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS began airing Sunday afternoon regular season games (non-exclusive) nationally in 2008, which was then replaced by Tuesday night games in 2022.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] From 2007 to 2020, TBS had its exclusive rights to any tiebreaker games that determine division or wild card champions.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It also airs exclusive coverage of the Division Series round of the playoffs.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] TBS carries the League Championship Series that are not included under Fox's television agreement; TBS shows the NLCS in odd-numbered years and the ALCS in even-numbered years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In January 2009, MLB launched MLB Network, featuring news and coverage from around the league, and airing 26 live games in the 2009 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Each team also has local broadcasts for all games not exclusively carried nationally.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] These games are typically split between a local broadcast television station and a local or regional sports network (RSN), though some teams only air local games through RSNs or through their own team networks.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] As Canada only contains one team, Sportsnet broadcasts Toronto Blue Jays games nationally.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel is owned by Rogers Communications, who is also the parent company of the Blue Jays.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Sportsnet also televises Fox's Saturday afternoon games, the All-Star Game, playoff games, and the World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In April 2011, TSN2 began carrying ESPN *Sunday Night Baseball* in Canada.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] TVA Sports airs Blue Jays games in French.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Several MLB games are broadcast exclusively on streaming television.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] After a year of exclusive games on Facebook, MLB partnered with YouTube to stream weekly games on the service beginning in the 2019 season, and extending until 2022.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2022, MLB made a deal with Apple Inc. to launch *Friday Night Baseball* on its Apple TV+ streaming service, and NBC Sports to broadcast *MLB Sunday Leadoff*, a package of early Sunday afternoon games on Peacock.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since the 2023 season's Division Series, HBO Max began simulcasting games broadcast by its sister network TBS (both owned by Warner Bros.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the 2024 season, The Roku Channel began streaming *MLB Sunday Leadoff*.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Announced in November 2025, MLB signed three-year media-rights deals with Netflix, ESPN, and NBCUniversal for the 2026 to 2028 seasons.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] A local broadcaster has priority to televise games of the team in their market over national broadcasters if the game is not exclusive to the national broadcaster.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] A market that has a local team playing in a non-exclusive game will receive an alternative programming feed on the national broadcaster.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB's streaming internet video service is also subject to the same blackout rules.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Commissioner Robert Manfred has expressed interest in changing the blackout policy to loosen the rules for streaming options.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The first baseball game ever broadcast on radio was a Pittsburgh Pirates versus Philadelphia Phillies game on August 5, 1921.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The game was broadcast by KDKA of Pittsburgh, and the Pirates defeated the Phillies 8–5.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] It was broadcast by KDKA staff announcer Harold Arlin.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] That year, KDKA and WJZ of Newark broadcast the first World Series on the radio, between the New York Giants and the New York Yankees, with Grantland Rice and Tommy Cowan calling the games for KDKA and WJZ, respectively.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] However, the broadcasters were not actually present at the game, but simply gave reports from a telegraph wire.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1922, WJZ broadcast the entire series, with Rice doing play-by-play.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] For the 1923 World Series, Rice was joined on Westinghouse for the first time by Graham McNamee.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] During the 1923 World Series, Rice was the main broadcaster, but during the fourth inning of Game 3, he turned the microphone over to McNamee.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] This was the start of McNamee's career, and McNamee became the first color commentator.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Although frequently criticized for his lack of expertise, McNamee helped popularize baseball.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 1998, national radio broadcasts moved to ESPN Radio.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN Radio currently broadcasts *Sunday Night Baseball* games during the regular season, as well as Saturday and occasional weekday games, along with the All-Star Game and all postseason contests.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2021, TUDN Radio airs Spanish-language coverage of select regular season and postseason games, including the World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, each team employs its own announcers, who broadcast during the regular season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Most teams operate regional networks to cover their fan bases; some of these supposedly regional networks (such as the New York Yankees Radio Network) have a national reach with affiliates located across the United States.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Major League Baseball has an exclusive rights deal with XM Satellite Radio, which includes the channel MLB Network Radio and live play-by-play of all games.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] MLB games are also broadcast live on the internet.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] All television and radio broadcasts of games are available via subscription to MLB.tv at Major League Baseball's website, MLB.com, and radio-only broadcasts are also available via subscription to MLB.com Gameday Audio.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In 2026, MLB.tv will be integrated into the ESPN App.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Since 2005, Major League Baseball has a partnership with XM Satellite Radio, launching a 24-7 channel, MLB Home Plate (now MLB Network Radio) which carries every major league game.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Games are also carried on MLB Gameday Audio.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] While all teams maintain a network of stations carrying their games in English, many teams also broadcast their games in Spanish, on a second network.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In addition, when the Washington Nationals were based in Montreal as the Montreal Expos, their games were broadcast in both English and French.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Some Toronto Blue Jays games have been broadcast in French as well.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Selected games of the Los Angeles Dodgers are broadcast in Korean by KMPC.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In modern years, teams have become increasingly reliant on local cable television rights fees, which grew unstable in the 2020s and which are not subject to equal revenue sharing.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Following the Disney-Fox merger, Disney divested Fox's regional broadcasting networks, which covered 14 of MLB's 30 teams, to Diamond Sports Network / Bally Sports.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Diamond filed for bankruptcy in 2023 and took advantage of debtor-friendly rules in the Bankruptcy Code to cancel or renegotiate its TV deals with a third of the league.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Teams that locked themselves into relatively stable deals near the peak of the market found themselves in a stronger financial position relative to the average team than ever before.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Critics respond that industry revenues and team valuations are still rising.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN broadcasts some MLB games in other countries, including ESPN Australia in Australia and New Zealand, ESPN Africa, and ESPN in the Netherlands.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In Mexico, until 2022, Fox Sports aired five regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Likewise, TUDN carried 4 matches a week until 2022: through the pay television signal, games were broadcast on Tuesdays and Thursdays, while on Saturdays (generally at 12:00 p.m.) and Sundays (rotating between NBA games, until the start of the NFL season) games were broadcast on Canal 9.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the Championship Series, it only broadcast one division and the whole World Series, these were broadcast on free-to-air television for 59 years.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2023 season, Imagen Televisión announced it would begin broadcasting a regular season game every Saturday and Sunday as well as the playoffs and the World Series on open television and its website in Mexico.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In Argentina, Fox Sports carries 5 regular season games per week and post-season games that belong to the league that broadcasts its American namesake (including the Wild Card Series).
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In Venezuela, since the 2016 season the cable channel IVC has the broadcast rights, they currently air 7 games per week.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Starting with the 2022 season, Televen broadcasts two games a week and the postseason on free-to-air TV While Venevisión, starting with the 2023 season, would return with the space "El Juego de la Semana" that carries a game every Sunday and non-working days on free-to-air television.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Dominican Republic since 2009 Grupo Altice has broadcast the entire regular season, playoffs and World Series through pay TV while on free-to-air television and radio Grupo Corripio airs 7 games per week and the entire postseason.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In Spain, Movistar Plus+ has the rights to broadcast the entire season, including one game daily, and the postseason, covering all games in the championship series and World Series.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Channel 5 in the United Kingdom previously screened MLB games, including the All-Star Game and postseason games, on Sunday and Wednesday, usually starting at 1 a.m.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Most recently, Johnny Gould and Josh Chetwynd presented *MLB on Five* on that station.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] The channel covered baseball beginning on its opening night in 1997, but for financial reasons, the decision was made not to pick up MLB for the 2009 season.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] BT Sport ESPN show live and recorded games several times a week—it is available with BT Sport and (on a subscriber-basis) Virgin Media in the UK.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] ESPN America televised many games in the UK and dozens of other countries; in May 2013, ESPN announced that it would shut down the channel on July 31, 2013.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In the Middle East, North Africa and France, MLB games are broadcast on beIN Sports channels.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] In Germany, Austria and Switzerland, as many as 500 MLB games will be broadcast from 2022 exclusively on the Sport1 platforms until 2026.
[src:ducky-yount/major-league-baseball-p02] Sport1 also broadcasts MLB games in Hungary, as of 2025.
